04253nam a22004455i 9780804764513DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047645137 a10.1515/97808047645132doi  a(DE-B1597)582146  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh1 aJohnson, Allen W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Evolution of Human Societies :bFrom Foraging Group to Agrarian State, Second Edition /cAllen W. Johnson, Timothy Earle. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (456 p.) :b9 tables, 13 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface to the Second Edition -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- t1 Introduction -- tPart I: The Family-Level Group -- t2 The Family Level -- t3 Family-Level Foragers -- t4 Families with Domestication -- tPart II: The Local Group -- t5 The Local Group -- t6 The Family and the Village -- t7 The Village and the Clan -- t8 The Corporate Group and the Big Man Collectivity -- tPart III: The Regional Polity -- t9 The Regional Polity -- t10 The Simple Chiefdom -- t11 The Complex Chiefdom -- t12 The Archaic State -- t13 The Peasant Economy in the Agrarian State -- t14 The Evolution of Global Society -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBy combining an original thesis and a representative body of ethnographic data, this ambitious work seeks to describe and explain the growth in complexity of human societies. Its emphasis is on the causes, mechanisms, and patterns of cultural evolution, which the authors explain in terms of a coherent theory of political economy—defined as the mobilization and exchange of goods and services between families. The authors show that the interconnected processes of technological change and population growth are the motor of social change, resulting in three related processes—intensification, integration, and stratification—that transform human societies over time. The validity of their theory rests on evidence drawn from 19 case studies that range widely over time and space. For this new edition, the authors have thoroughly rewritten the theoretical argument for greater clarity, updated the case materials to incorporate new research, and added a new chapter that applies their theoretical perspective to the problems of change since the industrial revolution and the globalization of trade and political influence. Reviews of the First Edition "In a book full of perceptive observations and persuasive arguments . . . Johnson and Earle show in masterly detail how societies articulate to their environments and . . . how they evolve." —Ethnohistory "A major contribution. . . . The book is a marvelous synthesis of ethnographic and historical data." —American Journal of Sociology "A large amount of research and thought has produced sensible and illuminating specific analyses of the mechanisms of evolutionary change. Another plus is that the writing is clear and the argument is neatly conceived." —American Anthropologist  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aAnthropology -- Cultural and Social Anthropology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aEarle, Timothy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476451340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764513423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804764513/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles